nrow(earnings_p)

2.2a) First, we will build an OLS model for predicting salary, using a forward stepwise selection approach to select our variables. Show all the relevant code for the stepwise model here: (Note: No need to include how you split the data) (3 points)

Answer:

First, we split the data (not evaluated) into a 80%-20% split:


set.seed(101)

train = sample(1:nrow(earnings_p),0.8*nrow(earnings_p))

train.data = earnings_p %>% slice(train)
test.data = earnings_p %>% slice(-train)

Then, we use a forward stepwise selection method, making sure we know how many predictors we have!


lm.full = lm(salary ~ . - sl_no, data = train.data)
totvar = length(lm.full$coefficients) - 1

set.seed(101)

lm.fwd = train(salary ~ . - sl_no, data = train.data,
               method = "leapForward",
               trControl = trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10),
               tuneGrid = data.frame(nvmax = 1:totvar))

  • 3 points: (i) Correct model (outcomes and predictors), (ii) correct method (leapForward), (iii) correct tuneGrid (1:14), (iv) correct data (train.data)

  • 1 point: One of the previous items is not correct.

  • 0 points: Any other case.

2.3a) Let’s now move on to regularization. Fit a ridge regression to predict the salary offer of a candidate. For a first pass, use a grid for the tuning parameter between 0 and 300,000 with a step of 5,000 between each. Show your code here: (5 points)

Answer: 


set.seed(101)

ridge = train(salary ~ . - sl_no, data = train.data,
            method = "glmnet",
            preProcess = "scale",
            trControl = trainControl("cv", number = 10),
            tuneGrid = expand.grid(alpha = 0,
                                   lambda = seq(0, 300000, by = 5000))
)

  • 5 points: (i) Correct model (outcomes and predictors), (ii) correct method (glmnet), (iii) correct tuneGrid (alpha = 0 and lambda provided), (iv) correct data (train.data)

  • 3 point: One of the previous items is not correct.

Task 3 - IBM knows you are leaving

Trying to predict the risk of losing an employee is critical if you want to keep talent within your company and avoid having a high turnover rate. For this task, you will be working with data from a company which contains information about employees and whether they left the company or not.

employees = read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/maibennett/sta235/main/exampleSite/content/Assignments/Homework/Homework5/data/employees.csv") %>% 
  select(-c(EmployeeCount, Over18, StandardHours))

Note: We remove three variables that have no variation in this dataset.

You can see a codebook of the variables here

Our goal is to best predict whether an employee will leave their company or not, given their characteristics.

For this task, use a seed of 122 before any code that uses some random selection. You can also use 10-fold cross-validation when needed, and an 70%-30% split for your training (train.data) and testing (test.data) datasets.

Note: Be sure to exclude (not drop) variables that are not predictors.

3.1) Let’s start preparing our data. Transform the variables Education, EnvironmentSatisfaction, JobInvolvement, JobSatisfaction, PerformanceRating, RelationshipSatisfaction, and WorkLifeBalance to categorical (factor) variables and split our data 70-30 for training and testing purposes. Show your code here: (4 points)

Answer: 

set.seed(122)

employees = employees %>% mutate(across(c(Education, EnvironmentSatisfaction,
                                          JobInvolvement, JobSatisfaction, PerformanceRating,
                                          RelationshipSatisfaction, WorkLifeBalance), 
                                        ~ as.factor(.x)))

n = nrow(employees)

train = sample(1:n, 0.7*n)

train.data = employees %>% slice(train)
test.data = employees %>% slice(-train)

  • 4 points: Correctly transforms the given variables into factors (either like this or one by one) and slices the data 70-30.

  • 2 points: One of the previous items is not correct.

  • 0 points: Any other case.

3.2) Let’s examine our data. Create a binary variable that takes the value of 1 if the employee’s job satisfaction is “High” or “Very high” and use that variable in addition to age, gender, marital status, and monthly income. Compare these characteristics between all employees that have quit and those who have not using a balance table. What can you say about these differences? Give an overall explanation and highlight some of the main differences/similarities. (8 points)

Answer: Looking at the table below, we can see that, on average, employees that quit have lower job satisfaction, tend to be younger, and more likely to be single. They also have, on average, lower income. There doesn’t seem to be a relevant spread between female employees or male employees that quit, though.


employees_bal = employees %>% mutate(HighJobSatisfaction = ifelse(JobSatisfaction=="3" | JobSatisfaction=="4", 1, 0),
                                      Female = ifelse(Gender == "Female", 1, 0),
                                      Married = ifelse(MaritalStatus=="Married", 1, 0),
                                      Single = ifelse(MaritalStatus=="Single", 1, 0),
                                      Divorced = ifelse(MaritalStatus=="Divorced", 1, 0)) %>%
  select(Attrition, HighJobSatisfaction, age, Female, Married, Single, Divorced, MonthlyIncome)

datasummary_balance(~ Attrition, data = employees_bal, dinm_statistic = "p.value", fmt = 2)

3.3a) Build a decision tree using 10-fold cross-validation for this task. Use a grid for the tuning parameter between 0 and 0.15, with length 100. Show your code here: (5 points)

Answer:


set.seed(122)

ct = train(
  factor(Attrition) ~ . - EmployeeNumber, data = train.data,
  method = "rpart",
  trControl = trainControl("cv", number = 10),
  tuneGrid = expand.grid(cp = seq(0, 0.15, length = 100))
)

  • 5 points: (i) Correct outcome (factor(Attrition)), (ii) Correct predictors (excludes EmployeeNumber), (iii) correct method (rpart), (iv) correct tuneGrid, (v) correct data (train.data)

3.6) Taking into account your previous results, what is one intervention that you would propose in your company to increase retention? (4 points)

Answer: It seems that individuals with less work experience that are asked to work overtime (and are paid separately for this) are the ones most likely to quit. Limiting overtime or changing the pay structure for these individuals might be a way to increase retention, in addition to increasing wages.
